For the thousandth time, Piqa wondered what had possessed the Dark Elf to ask for this interview. <i>"Not Dark Elf"</i> she caught herself. <i>"Teir'Dal, always refer to them as Teir'Dal."</i>. She resolved to make it one of her first questions, indirectly of course. She began to run her questions over in her mind and grew calmer as the familiar routine she had used many times before settled in her mind. She had chosen the location well, a table in the corner of the room, far from any other tables, with the backs of both chairs against the wall, no sense in upsetting her client.<br>
Piqa looked up as the door to the common room of the tavern opened with a creek and felt her pulse quicken as three cloaked Dark Elves strode into the room. There was an instant silence as the occupants regarded the new entrants with a mixture of hate and fear. The Dark Elves returned the gazes directed at them in stoic silence and Piqa had time to look them over closely. The two flanking ones looked like bodyguards, they were slightly taller than the central one and looked over the patrons with eyes that saw weapons, armor and positions, warrior's gazes. And there could be no doubt to whom the central one was. Commander Elhimac let his gaze slide across the room until he locked eyes with her, and for a brief second Piqa felt as if those eyes were stripping the layers from her mind like layers off an onion and examining her soul with scientific interest.<br>
The moment passed and the Dark Elves began to move over to her table. Piqa noticed that a path was quickly cleared for them and that the patrons occupying the tables around her suddenly acquired a new interest for the bar in the other end of the room.<br>
Piqa began to stand up and greet Elhimac<br>
"Ahh, Commander Elhimac, it is a pleasure to.."<br>
<br>
"You may disperse with the pleasantries, Ms Ravenheart." He waved his hand in dismissal, "we both know that neither you nor I find this terribly pleasant, so let us get to business." He said in a low voice, though Piqa noted that his words carried clearly and that if he raised his voice he could probably be heard in the middle of a raging battle.<br>
<br>
"Very well." She said, somewhat taken aback at this turn of events. Elhimac snapped his fingers and his guards seated themselves at a neighbouring table while Elhimac took the seat across from hers. <br>
<br>
"But if it is not pleasant, then why are you here at all ?" she inquired, anxious to pursue the matter before it slipped.<br>
<br>
His otherwise perpetual frown softened into a faint smile, and Piqa noticed that if it hadn't been for his hard eyes and stern face, then his shiny blue skin and pearly white hair would have been attractive.<br>
"Very simple," he said in a patronising tone "control of the media, control of the mind. There have been a great number of leaders from various mercenary guilds who have made use of your skills. Some of them to throw scorn upon the Teir'Dal and demonise us."<br>
<br>
"Very well, let us start from the beginning." Piqa took up a quill and a sheet of paper to take notes and began her interview. "Might I ask how you came into your present position ?"   <i>How did you get interested in EQ?</i><br>
<br>
He leaned back in his chair and let his eyes gaze into the distance. "I was idle." He said, memories making him forget to harden his voice. "I had recently completed a long and painful journey, someone close to me had passed away and I needed something to distract myself. An idle mind is a wasted mind." His face began to grow back into a scowl and Piqa quickly launched into her next question, making a mental note not to pursue that matter of his past too closely.<br>
<br>
"You have come a long way indeed. If you look at yourself now, how would you best define yourself ?" <i>What is the name/class/race/level/gender of your primary Character?</i><br>
<br>
"I am a Knight." He said, and Piqa noticed an undercurrent of pride in his voice. "I am born a Teir'Dal and I am proud to follow the duty laid out for me by my birth. I may not be the best of warriors in a direct battle, but one would do well to remember that solely because I have only been trained a total of 30 months in fighting skills does not make me less dangerous. There is much more to battle than merely fighting." His lips parted in a smile at this last sentence, as if he knew something that no one else did.   <br>
<br>
"And what is your full name if I may ask ?" Piqa said, her quill taking notes from time to time.<br>
<br>
Elhimac looked at her in a curious way. "You may ask, but that is no guarantee that I will answer. I am Elhimac, that is all you will need to know."<br>
This was not exactly turning out the way she had imagined, most of her clients would have thumped their chests and proudly given their entire name and their far too many titles. <br>
  <br>
 "I see" Piqa said; though she didn't. "And have you always felt that calling to be a Knight, or were you ever in doubt ?" <i>Is your main character now your first or did you start as something else?</i><br>
<br>
At this moment, the drinks she had ordered in advance arrived, it was always a good idea to have a distraction like this and a glass in front of them. The waiter set down a mug of foaming ale in front of her and placed a glass of deep purple liquid in front of Commander Elhimac, which was not at all what she had ordered for him. Piqa looked up and saw that the waiter was not the usual waiter either, but someone she had never seen before though she frequented this place very much. She looked down at her ale with new-found suspicion.<br>
<br>
"Come now." Her client said to her "Why would I do such a thing ?" Obviously he had noticed her apprehensive gaze. Piqa took her mug and raised it in a tentative salute to her companion before taking a very tender sip. It tasted very much like ale. <br>
"Right, now about…"<br>
<br>
"I have never been in doubt. It has been my duty to assume this position." He answered her. " I am me, and I have always been." He said with finality taking another sip from his glass.<br>
<br>
"Very well, and how long have you been in service ?" she asked, deciding to go for the direct approach <i>When was he/she born according to the /played date?</i><br>
<br>
"What matters seniority ? It is our abilities that define us not how long we have pursued our chosen path. But if you insist, then I have been in service ever since July of the year 2000" Piqa felt her eyes grow wide at this, she knew that elves could be incredibly old without showing it, but this made him older than Highpass Keep.<br>
 <br>
"I see, and how dedicated would you say that you have been ? " <br>
<i>How many days played does this character have?</i><br>
 <br>
Elhimac looked up at her with a sudden anger in his eyes.<br>
"Are you suggesting that I have been less than faithful ?" His voice was suddenly very menacing and Piqa felt the air around her go cold. <br>
<br>
"Of course not!" she quickly answered. <br>
<br>
"Good, because it would not be well if it came across that I was not dedicated." Piqa heard the threat in his words.<br>
<br>
"Well let us talk about your Guard then." Piqa stated, wanting to move on to less touchy subjects. <i>Do you belong to a guild?</i><br>
<br>
"Ahh yes the Phantom Guard." Elhimac drew his cloak aside and tapped a small silver badge upon his tunic. <br>
<br><img src="http://www.winterblood.com/mmrp/pgbadge_med.gif"><br><br>
"I was appointed to the commanding post of the newly created Phantom Guard by her majesty Queen Cristianos of Neriak." Piqa suppressed an involuntary shiver at the name. "The Guards job amongst other things is to police Neriak and ensure that dissident persons do not get out of hand. And our duties often take us abroad." He stated matter of factly. "Spies and traitors like to use innocent neutral cities for their base of operations." Piqa suspected that there was much more to the Phantom Guard than he was letting on, but she knew better than to ask.<br>
 <br>
"Very satisfactory" she said, though she suspected that he knew that she didn't really think so. "You said you were appointed, did the Phantom Guard then exist before you were given the Commanding post ? And in such case, what if its history before your appointment ?" <br>
<i>How did you come to join your guild?</i><br>
<br>
"No, the Guard did not exist before I created it. I was given the title, the task, and a few volunteers and told to do the rest. I flatter myself that I succeeded quite well, though the beginning had its turbulent times."<br>
<br>
"Getting back to you as a person, have you ever been in the service of another guild ?" <i>Have you ever belonged to another guild?</i><br>
<br>
Elhimac looked up at the ceiling and half-closed his eyes. "Yes, one." He said with deep disdain. "An ineffectual one, an outfit by the name of Tel'aran'rhiod. It was run by an incompetent and absentminded spellcaster who had been placed in the position through political manoeuvring. What a fool! He would often lock himself away and busy himself with magical experiments just when he was needed the most. He was finally removed from the position and cast down." Piqa did not need to ask what became of him. She could guess all too well.<br>
 <br>
"Well then, you are a much more capable leader hopefully." She said in an effort to sound friendly and pave the way for her next questions. "And what do you like best about the position as Commander ?" <i>What do you like best about your guild?</i><br>
<br>
 "I am not supposed to like my position, I am supposed to do my duty, whether I like it or not is irrelevant." He suddenly smiled. "But as it happens I do like to hold the commanding post. That unequalled sense of accomplishment when a mission is accomplished or a goal is reached."<br>
<br>
Piqa smiled in return "and what do you like least then ?"<br>
<i>What do you like least?</i><br>
 <br>
Elhimac smiled sadly. "The best soldiers are the ones who are the hardest to keep in line. And my Guards are very good soldiers." He added with not-so-hidden implication and took another sip of his drink.<br>
<br>
"Tell me a bit about the accomplishments of your Guard then, you mentioned that your job consisted of rooting out 'dissidents' ?"<br>
<br>
"Yes, outlaws, renegades, those who would seek to gain profit for themselves by hurting the greater whole of the Teir'Dal." He looked into the distance as he recalled memories.<br>
"There was a cult. The Quellar'Vos'Velkyn. They preached a radical form of worship and praised anarchy and disorder as the sublime movers of states. They were a potential danger. They were purged." Piqa gulped <br>
"And of course, some dangers are not from within but from without. My duty to ensure peace and order amongst the Teir'Dal often brings the Guard into conflict with those who would seek our downfall." There was a hint of bitterness in his voice when he spoke of the downfall of Neriak.<br>
"Amongst our most bitter enemies is the remnants of the fallen House Winterblood. Some time ago we found out that one of their number possessed information that would bring about great disasters if this information fell into the hands of the wrong people. We sought to eliminate this treat to the security of Norrath by silencing this particular person. Unfortunately, she escaped our reach and have since wrongfully convinced House Winterblood that we are seeking to cause distress for them. They have foolishly believed her and decided to marshal their forces in an attempt to destroy us." Piqa didn't know if she should be cheering for the Winterbloods or not, she decided against it. Stay professional, she told herself.<br>
 <br>
"Most interesting, and what of your personal life Commander ? Are you married ?"<br>
<i>(Is your character single ? Who is your significant other ?) </i><br>
Something akin to a flicker of amusement crossed Elhimac's face before he managed to catch it. <br>
<br>
"No, I am not. I have little time for such frivolities now."<br>
His use of the word now seemed to suggest that there was a deeper story here, but with his refusal to discuss matters of his personal past Piqa decided to let the unspoken question go.<br>
<br>
"Well then, you must surely have seen a lot of combat and battle in your time as Commander."<br>
<i>What is your most memorable raid? Please describe.</i><br>
  <br>
Elhimac smiled sadly "Indeed I have, but I fear most of it is not of the sort that you have in mind. There have been no pitched battles, no heroic last stands, no tale-worthy epic fights. The duty of the Guard makes stealth and subterfuge take the high seat. Though before I was made Commander there was one occasion worthy of note."<br>
He took another small sip of his wine-like liquid and began his tale.<br>
<br>
"It was many years ago. But even at that time I was an apprentice squire in the service of Neriak. An informer had been traced to the thieves guild of Freeport, and I had been sent abroad along with a member of the Priesthood to dispose of him. But when we reached his hideout in the sailors' section of Freeport we found our quarry gone. A quick check with the authorities showed us that he had left town that very morning in a great hurry heading east.<br>
We picked up his trail in the sandy regions of the Commonlands valley, where the grass gives way to the intruding desert. We tracked him deep into the commonlands and his tracks began to turn slowly to the Southeast, towards the mountains. Thinking that we would catch up with him when the rocky regions slowed his progress we picked up our pace.<br>
We followed his tracks across the dunes and though we saw no sign of the renegade, his tracks lead us to an old abandoned ruin, almost buried in the billowing sand. Ruins like these dotted the region. They are remnants of an old and almost forgotten empire of the Elves.  We knew we had our prey, for there were rarely other exits from those ruins. We cautiously entered the fallen outpost, our eyes shifting to allow for the darkness, along the entranceway, we could dimly spy the footprints in the dust that marked our target's way into the silent halls.<br>
The aeons had not been kind to the ruin, and twice we were forced to take shelter as loose bricks and mortar came crumbling down from the ceiling threatening a cave-in. <br>
As we drew farther from the entrance, ancient bones and skeletons began to litter the place showing that the inhabitants had not abandoned their home quietly. My companion guessed that the Civil War that tore the Elven realm apart were to blame. <br>
We found our target deep within the ruin. Dead. His face was frozen in a rictus of horror and his hair was white as a sheet. It looked like he had died of fright.<br>
We took proof of his demise and began to search the corpse to assure ourselves that he had not written his information down somewhere. But as I was looking through his backpack and my companion was rummaging through his clothes, the most unnatural thing happened: A soft moan echoed through the hall where the corpse lay. We jumped up and reached for our arms, looking around for a the source of the sound. But as it was repeated, we became aware that the moan had come from the lips of the dead man. We watched with beating hearts as a spasm ran through the corpse and the dead man sat up, his face still locked in its dreadful state. He drew himself to his feet and began to scramble towards us, hands reaching forward as if to embrace us. But when he drew close, I swung my blade at his head and took it clean off his shoulders, it clattered against the floor, but still the dead man refused to fall, his headless body came on, never breaking its stride. My companion smashed a mace against the unliving mans chest, smashing apart his torso like an over-ripe fruit and this time the zombie fell and did not rise again.<br>
Standing there in the darkness, getting our wits back, we suddenly became aware that the moaning had not stopped. I went over and examined the bodiless head and sure enough, beyond all reason, the head continued its mournful song. I crushed the head against the wall, and silence closed in on the ruin once more. But it was a short respite, for far-off, like an echo that refused to die, that ghastly moaning continued. Now thoroughly shaken, we wasted no time debating over our course of action but started for the exit at a brisk pace, not quite a run but no walk either.<br>
The echoes of the mournful song, for that is how I can best describe it, in the confined tunnels played havoc with our hearing, one moment seeming to come from far-off, the next from around the corner. Presently another sound was added to the dead song, the clatter and rattle of bones. <br>
We paused in a hallway on hearing that disturbing sound and from the hallway ahead emerged the source of the bony rattling: Animated skeletons, marching forth like soldiers from long forgotten graves still clutching the weapons they had fought with millennia ago. The skeletons of the long-dead defenders had risen again to repel our incursion. <br>
We held our weapons high and prepared to lay the undead back into their graves and presently fear and doubt vanished in the flurry and chaos of battle at close quarters. The foes had to be literally hacked apart before they would succumb to defeat. I saw single skeletal arms, parted from their rightful bodies, still wave their weapons and seek to pierce our feet. I cleaved one rotting corpse in two at the waist and yet the legs continued to kick at me and the upper body lifted itself up by the arms and resumed its fight. <br>
Then all of a sudden we had reduced the last of them to little more than chips and dust. The silence seemed unreal compared to the din that had reigned just before. Though from the depths of the hall we had come from, our ears could pick out the rattling sound once more. The corpses that must surely lie deeper inside the ruin was likewise awakened. This would not do, already, wounds and gashes adorned our bodies like jewellery upon a maid. We found what last energies we had and ran in the direction we hoped was the exit.<br>
It was the correct direction and in little more than a minute's running through those crumbling halls we spied the dim sunlight shining. But we were not alone in the entrance hall anymore. Down in the shadows of the opening in the mountains, the sunlight was blocked by a tall, rangy figure clad in rags. For a brief instant we took him for a beggar or a vagabond, come to seek shelter for the night. But then we saw the lack of flesh upon his frame and the sickly green glow that shined out of the mummy's eyeholes. Our exit was blocked and behind us we could heard that doomladen rattling coming closer.<br>
We both knew that we had not the strength to fight our way out into freedom. Though the mummy made no move to advance towards us, perhaps it desired its undead companions to join in the slaughter, our doom seemed assured and our bones fated to become part of the mindless legion that defended this ruin for all eternity.<br>
As remorse gripped our hearts an idea formed in my head, born from defiance and desperation. Years ago when I was still being taught the ways of the Knight, our mentor in the arts of magic had taught us a cantrip to render the caster impervious to the eyes of those dead. I had thought it a foolish waste of time to study and had suffered a beating for my lack of diligence. But now the words of the spell intruded upon my mind, along with a twinge in my back where my mentors lash had made its mark. <br>
But now the words and the manipulation of the ether came clearly to me and I cast the spell twice, once for my priestly friend and once for myself. It did not feel like much, only a slight tingling of the skin. My companion whispered a prayer and then marched towards the mummy and the exit beyond, and I followed suit. <br>
The passage was small and the mummy stood clean in the middle, making only a small passage on either side available. My companion pressed his back to the wall and the slowly edged past the mummy and it seemed to work, the mummy made no move whatsoever and my anxiety fell a bit.<br>
The rattling sound became louder and in the dim darkness one could spy movement down in the depths of the ruin, there were no time to waste, so I pressed my back to the wall and began to slowly edge my way past the bandage wrapped corpse. It seemed to me that surely the thing must somehow hear my breath or the clank of my armor, but it made no move what so ever until I was right beside it. Then it turned its head and looked strait at me with those sickly green orbs that floated in its eyeholes. I felt the fertid stench of thousand year old rags upon my face and I thought that I was dead. <br>
But I had thought too soon, for having seemingly looked right through me, it turned its head back in the other direction and I scrambled past it with my heart in my throat. We ran out into the evening sunlight, and though the undead did not pursue us beyond the entrance to their lair, we did not stop running until we could no longer see the entrance to that cursed ruin."<br>
